WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.360
[Amit Varma]: The seen and the unseen would not exist if not for serendipity.

00:00:08.360 --> 00:00:11.760
[Amit Varma]: Five and a half years ago, I congratulated a friend on his podcast.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:15.040
[Amit Varma]: The owner of the network he was with said, Hey, why don't you try podcasting?

00:00:15.040 --> 00:00:17.040
[Amit Varma]: We started talking and the show was born.

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:21.480
[Amit Varma]: I've elaborated on the origin story in episode 202 58 of the show.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:25.120
[Amit Varma]: The point is that it began because of a happy accident.

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:27.820
[Amit Varma]: And I was open to that happy accident happening.

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:32.600
[Amit Varma]: Since then, many episodes of the show have happened because I left space for serendipity.

00:00:32.600 --> 00:00:36.520
[Amit Varma]: As my guest today would say, I met someone interesting at a gathering, or I picked up

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:41.040
[Amit Varma]: a book casually somewhere, or I entered a rabbit hole and found an interesting person

00:00:41.040 --> 00:00:42.040
[Amit Varma]: waiting for me.

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:46.040
[Amit Varma]: Being an introvert who doesn't like to party, I don't quote serendipity as much as I would

00:00:46.040 --> 00:00:47.040
[Amit Varma]: like to.

00:00:47.040 --> 00:00:50.640
[Amit Varma]: But so much that is good in my life began as a happy accident.

00:00:50.640 --> 00:00:55.360
[Amit Varma]: The friends I have, the books that shaped me, the ways in which I changed as a person.

00:00:55.360 --> 00:01:00.180
[Amit Varma]: So even though I often like to be alone, I also try these days to leave a little space

00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:02.080
[Amit Varma]: for these accidents to happen.

00:01:02.080 --> 00:01:06.680
[Amit Varma]: John Lennon once said, life is what happens to you when you're busy making other plans.

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:11.280
[Amit Varma]: I say let it happen.

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:16.680
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:17.680
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:23.600
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:25.020
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:01:25.020 --> 00:01:29.880
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Abhijit Bhaluri, who started off living a conventional life, made a little

00:01:29.880 --> 00:01:35.000
[Amit Varma]: space for serendipity, kept himself open to new experiences, and shifted neatly from a

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.320
[Amit Varma]: corporate career to the creator economy.

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:42.320
[Amit Varma]: Abhijit has written many books on his journey, the latest being Dreamers and Unicorns, and

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.880
[Amit Varma]: they all come as a culmination of a process.

00:01:45.880 --> 00:01:51.480
[Amit Varma]: First he leaves himself open to experiences, then he learns from them and forms frameworks

00:01:51.480 --> 00:01:53.040
[Amit Varma]: to understand them.

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:57.040
[Amit Varma]: After that, he applies those frameworks in other contexts to understand the world and

00:01:57.040 --> 00:01:58.920
[Amit Varma]: his own self a little better.

00:01:58.920 --> 00:02:03.840
[Amit Varma]: And finally, he teaches them to others, either in real or virtual classrooms or through books

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:04.840
[Amit Varma]: and videos.

00:02:04.840 --> 00:02:09.040
[Amit Varma]: I found this process fascinating, and I loved hearing about Abhijit's journey.

